// HaerDalis - Garrick
@0 = ~Haer'Dalis... ~
@1 = ~You have my full attention, my young colleague.~
@2 = ~Tell me, Haer'Dalis, do I truly have real minstrel talent?~
@3 = ~Oh...? I thought you had no doubt about that.~
@4 = ~I doubt it sometimes, to be honest. I just hide it carefully. But you traveled through the Planes, saw and heard a lot, and finally you yourself are very talented. I will be able to appreciate your... as befits... well... your honestly...~
@5 = ~My inspired child, I can say one thing; talent is half the battle. You can't do without it, but you have to work hard to polish this diamond to a breathtaking shine. Everyone has heard about it, but not everyone is using it in practice. Stubbornly, do not indulge yourself, and you will conquer Faerun.~
@6 = ~Oh thanks! ~
@7 = ~Yes, one of the best artists on all the Planes is telling you this! *Laughs* Don't be offended that I tease you a little, spring bird, I really believe in your gift and your future.~
@8 = ~Thank you, Haer'Dalis. Think we'll be friends?~ [GARRICK4]
@9 = ~No doubt about it, friend.~

// Aerie - Garrick 2 (after Underdark)
@10 = ~Aerie, how are you feeling?~
@11 = ~I... not bad. Why are you asking?~
@12 = ~Because I read that avariel elves do not tolerate confined spaces, and I wondered how you endured all these horrible adventures in the Underdark... without a sky above your head.~
@13 = ~I don't know myself. M-maybe I'm not as much an avariel as I used to be? I felt very b-bad. But I endured. I just couldn't let everyone down. I tried to think of good things... I even tried... to appreciate the beauty of all those glowing mushrooms, carved columns... but I was so happy to be on the surface again!~
@14 = ~You're good person, Aerie. I feel very humbled to be travelling with someone such as you.~
@15 = ~*Smiles* Thank you. You shouldn't overpraise me, although i do appreciate your participation in this group and your courtesy towards me. I Hope you can give me a couple of pages in your book?~
@16 = ~You can have as many as you want, Aerie! After all, overcoming yourself is real heroism, and everyone should know about real heroes.~ [GARRICKU]
@17 = ~*Smiles*~

// Imoen - Garrick
@18 = ~Hey Sir Garrick! ~
@19 = ~I'm listening, sly little girl.~ [GARRICKG]
@20 = ~I'm not that little, plus I have a question for you.~
@21 = ~Yes? ~
@22 = ~A very important question.~
@23 = ~I have no doubt about it.~
@24 = ~A very, very, very important question. Where about does the brave Sir Garrick place in his book Imoen the Magnificent?~
@25 = ~Imoen the... what?~
@26 = ~Imoen the Mag-nif-i-cent! A brave heroine, under whose tutelage <CHARNAME> confronted the powerful and insidious Sarevok. It cannot be that you do not praise this heroine in your composition, as she deserves right?~
@27 = ~You're confusing something. After all, <CHARNAME> would have failed on that tremendous adventure had it not been for the guidance of Sir Garrick. ~
@28 = ~Sir, let me disagree with you. You clearly underestimate Imoen's influence on the critical events of the time when she and her aide <CHARNAME> ended the war between Amn and Baldur's Gate. ~
@29 = ~Remember that it's Sir Garrick...~
@30 = ~Listen, SIR! Imoen is not only gorgeous but also generous. She agrees to share with you a part of her brilliant fame... Even half the glory, if you sing poetry of her amazing beauty, flexibility and grace, sleight of hand (although the latter, you could probably keep that part out) and place these verses in your book.~
@31 = ~But there is to be one condition. Poems should be, like Imoen herself; mag-nif-i-cent.~
@32 = ~Gladly, my heroic lady!~
@33 = ~That's great. I knew that we would agree on this. He he... Garrick, you're a remarkable guy.~
@34 = ~Also what is great is that we're friends, aren't we? Good, kind, powerful friends whose union can shake the world!~

// Viconia - Garrick
@35 = ~Viconia, you belong to House De'Vir, right? It has a dark history, right? I heard...~
@36 = ~Shut up iblith. The fact that an insignificant rivvil like you managed to hear something about my house somewhere out of the corner of his ear does not give him the right to rant about what he does not understand at all.~
@37 = ~I just wanted to ask...~
@38 = ~I'm not going to satisfy your pathetic curiosity. ~
@39 = ~Listen, Viconia... It is as fate dictated that you live among the landlings you despise. But we have something new for you. Your people, they say, do not have such concepts as kindness, friendship, love... So why not try to comprehend all this, at least a little? What if you like it?~
@40 = ~As I said before iblith, I'm not going to satisfy your pathetic curiosity.~
@41 = ~*Viconia gives Garrick a contemptuous look and turns away* ~

// Dorn - Garrick
@42 = ~*Looks grimly at Garrick* So what is this misunderstanding doing in our group?~
@43 = ~Dorn, aren't you on the wrong foot? Well after thinking about it, you probably have been all the time though.~
@44 = ~Don't mock me, you lout. I'll knock you down with one strike. You are such a pitiful sight, a man who thinks he is doing a great thing by singing songs.~
@45 = ~A pitiful sight indeed, a blockhead who does not realize what beauty and pure joy are.~
@46 = ~Talk, talk, talk... I refuse to listen to your drivel, pathetic one.~
@47 = ~Enjoy your day too. ~

// Anomen - Garrick
@48 = ~Anomen... May I ask, why did you decide to become a knight?~ [GARRICKX]
@49 = ~You may ask, but I have no desire to answer this question for you.~
@50 = ~Why is your response so unfriendly?~ [GARRICK8]
@51 = ~Fine, what do you want to hear, bard?~
@52 = ~I thought you tasted for fame. I could compose a song about your exploits. But I wanted to start from early childhood.~ [GARRICKY]
@53 = ~Then remember to write about my mother's death. And about how my drunken of a father, having found me reading a chivalric novel, tore it out of my hands and threw it into the fire and abused me for it. Then write about how he insulted my sister, who tried to intercede for me. Also one day... No what, enough, just leave me be.~
@54 = ~Anomen, it's very sad to hear all this. But if you are offended by your father, why do you repeat his behavior?~
@55 = ~What are you talking about, Garrick? ~
@56 = ~You are just as willing to offend anyone who annoys you in any way, even if no one is to blame but you. Although that won't protect yourself from that old pain, and you won't be able to hide from the world's anger.~
@57 = ~I refuse to listen to any more of your nonsense. As I said before, leave me be.~
@58 = ~Still, you are thinking, I can see it. In the meantime, I will compose a bright and kind song about you!~

// Neera - Garrick
@59 = ~Aye Garrick! I'm sorry... I'm sorry, I didn't mean it.~
@60 = ~Oh, Neera, this is my manuscript. You almost burned it.~ [GARRICKL]
@61 = ~Yes... I see. I just... wanted to put some magical protection on you. After all, enemies can appear at any moment, and you are so fragile... and it would not hurt you. But you see... *With tears in her voice* It's always like this for me...~
@62 = ~Thank you for your concern, Neera, but do not worry. You will see, next time you will succeed.~ [GARRICK4]
@63 = ~*Smiles* Thank you for your support, Garrick. You are very good friend.~

// Cernd - Garrick
@64 = ~Don't you think, bard, that all your songs are losing out to the natural music of nature? Even the most inspired compositions of people are nothing in front of the murmur of a stream or the sounds of a night forest... ~
@65 = ~Yes Cernd, sometimes it does occurs to me. But this is what I thought: Why not consider people as a part of nature, and their songs as a continuation of its enchanting sound?~ [GARRICKN]
@66 = ~People bring too much aggressive passion to what they do.~
@67 = ~But nature can also be aggressively passionate. You know that.~
@68 = ~Yes, but nature is much more honest. However... I'm not saying I don't like your songs at all, Garrick. At least when you sing, I don't want to cover my ears.~

// Rasaad - Garrick
@69 = ~I want to tell you, young poet, that Selune's light shines upon you. ~
@70 = ~There is a lot of praise in your lips, Rasaad. You are so deeply devoted to your deity. I also honor Milil, the god of songs and poetry, but far from becoming a priest or a monk.~
@71 = ~You are already serving your god in the most pleasing way for him. Happy are the people who have found their true path in this life. ~


// Nalia - Garrick 1
@72 = ~Garrick...~
@73 = ~Yes, Nalia?~ [GARRICKG]
@74 = ~I should probably apologize again... for my aunt. Well, she is who she is. But I thought you were hurt by her appeal. ~
@75 = ~No, no, Nalia, you don't have to apologize at all. You are absolutely right, she is so... Many nobles grow up with similar beliefs and pass them on to their children. I just involuntarily remembered how difficult it was to perform in front of aristocrats who liked to emphasize that the artists, in their opinion, were rabble and fit only to entertain them. They gave us the payment for the performance as a donation... but this is all in the past, and it is not worth mentioning at all.~
@76 = ~Although I am also a noblewoman, this way of thinking is alien to me! I will never humiliate a person for their poverty or simple origin. I... my mother was not at all like Aunt Delcia, she loved people and helped them as best she could, and I try to be like her.~
@77 = ~I wouldn't even think of comparing you to your aunt. We barely know each other, but I feel that you are a kind and glorious person. A bard's sense, you know...~
@78 = ~Thank you Garrick! You are also good, it is so pleasant and easy to talk to you, but best we get going. Let's chat some more in the future.~
@79 = ~I'd love to!~ [GARRICKS]

// Nalia - Garrick 2
@80 = ~Garrick, can I talk to you for a bit? ~
@81 = ~Of course, my lady!~ [GARRICKG]
@82 = ~*Laughs* Oh Sir Garrick, you have great manners, but I wanted to talk about not-so-pleasant things...~
@83 = ~Last time you said it hurt you when arrogant listeners paid to perform as if they were giving alms. But if alms are given to those who need them, just like that, without swagger? That doesn't mean you're humiliating the poor, is it?~
@84 = ~Honestly, I don’t know how I would answer if I didn’t know what hunger was. It was a very short period in my life when I had to part with the troupe in which I played. Until the lead met a woman for whom he began to work, he performed as best he could. And now I understand: if you share from the heart with those who are in need, there can be no humiliation here.~
@85 = ~Oh, Garrick. Maybe I seem to you a naive girl who plays charity out of boredom, having no idea what real need and suffering are? I know a lot of people look at me like that.~
@86 = ~No, of course not! It is called very simply, a kind heart. True, I never asked for alms. I sang, played and somehow earned money for a stew in a tavern. And then everything changed for the better.~
@87 = ~Yet your life hasn't been easy... compared to mine. ~
@88 = ~Or maybe just the opposite? I didn't lose loved ones. And I really sympathize with you. ~
@89 = ~Thank you Garrick. We've haven't known each other for so long, but I feels we've been friends for a long time.~
@90 = ~I feel the same way.~

